ns v. Harvard and University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, Foley explores how organizations have resisted and complied with public policies regarding race. She examines how admissions officers, who have played an important role in the long fight to protect racial diversity in higher education, work around the law to maintain diversity after affirmative action is banned. Foley takes us behind the curtain of student admissions, shedding light on how multiple universities, including the University of Michigan, have creatively responded to affirmative action bans. On the Basis of Race traces the history of a controversial idea and policy, and provides insight into its uncertain future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAffirmative action programs in educationzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in higher educationzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aHigher education and statezUnited States. 0aMulticultural educationzUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / Federal Legislation.2bisacsh  aAmerican political development.  aAmerican racial politics.  aStudents for Fair Admission.  aaffirmative action.  adesegregation.  aintegration.  alaw-in-action.  alegal mandate.  aracial diversity and admissions.  aracial politics.  aresistant compliance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479821686.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479821686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479821686/original  a978-3-11-075163-5  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles